<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>In the Virtual Observatory, most the data will be remote.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>The remote data volume may be huge;</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>Thus, astronomy data on the Grid will generally reside in read-intensive databases that will be accessed by associative query interfaces that subset the data.</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>Thus, the archives have only 12% of the total data and less than 25% of the public data (data is typically made public after a year).</a>
<a name="4">[4]</a> <a href="#4" id=4>The huge data volumes require a parallel search capability with direct random access of certain objects.</a>
<a name="5">[5]</a> <a href="#5" id=5>Therefore, while every instrument produces a steady data stream, there is an ever more complex worldwide network of facilities with large output data sets.</a>
<a name="6">[6]</a> <a href="#6" id=6>As the amount of data is doubling every year, in three years the data grows by eightfold.</a>
<a name="7">[7]</a> <a href="#7" id=7>therefore, it makes sense to move as much of the data processing as near the data as possible, because in many cases after the first few steps of processing the output volume is dramatically smaller (e.g., extracting object catalogs).</a>
<a name="8">[8]</a> <a href="#8" id=8>As more and more data access is through automated facilities, it is increasingly important to capture the details of how the data was derived and calibrated.</a>
